La Palina is a great Italian restaurant with amazing food that has been family owned for over 90 years. The atmosphere is cozy and the staff which is mostly family makes you feel like you are part of their family when you dine there. The food is delicious the Sunday sauce never disappoints with their meatballs and sausage. I live in New Jersey but if I'm in Brooklyn I go in for dinner they are worth the trip.

My family has used this place for at-home catering. The manager was very friendly and courteous and the portions were plentiful. For my father's birthday we decided to visit the restaurant. He was visiting from out of town and we were looking forward to treating him to good quality Italian cuisine. We were surprised when the food arrived how bland it tasted but the worst part of the meal was that almost all of the dishes arrived on the table overcooked and burnt. After we reluctantly finished our meal and requested the check (of which we had to ask for twice), the restaurant worker who seated us rudely commented that he would have given the check if we'd asked before. Considering that the restaurant had been nearly empty at the time, I was surprised that he had forgotten that we had asked for the check already. Not wanting to ruin my father's birthday, we left without complaint. Later on my dad stated that this was the worst place that he'd went to on one of his birthdays.

We initially saw this restaurant on Leah Remini's show.  When we came back to visit friends and family a few months ago, we decided to come for dinner.  Let me begin by saying that the staff is amazing.  From making the reservation to paying the check, everything, and I do mean everything was absolutely fantastic.  We began with several appetizers and antipasti, and moved onto the main dishes.  After, we shared deserts, which were heavenly.  If you are fortunate enough to live close to this establishment, you need to visit.  If you're planning a visit to New York, rent a car and visit La Palina for dinner.  It will be an experience you will never forget.  Presently, we are planning to re-locate back to Brooklyn.  When we do, our first dinner back home will be at La Palina with friends and family.

We had my daughter's baby shower at La Paulina. They provided good food, excellent service and helped make the party a success. It was reasonably priced and they added excellent vegetarian options on their price fixed menu.

Nice old school Italian restaurant with amazing food.  My mom had the gnocchi, one of the tougher Italian pasta to make and cook properly.  "This is only the third time in my life I've had good gnocchi in a restaurant."  The manicotti was to die for- the ricotta was spot on and the sauce perfect.  The decor is classic Italian restaurant and the waiters a bunch of good guys.  Valet parking.  All in all, a thumbs up.

Evening was wonderful - food is very good. Everything was great, We can't drink alcohol. We ordered salad, two main entrees and coffee. There was karaoke which added to the evening. We were enjoying everything when the waiter comes over and says you have to leave. We need your table. You aren't eating or drinking. Never in our lives in the states or abroad has this ever happened. Totally lost respect for this restaurant. I saw others not drinking alcoholic beverages, but they staggered their orders and shared dishes, but they were known by the establishment. So I guess you can't be a newcomer there. Too bad. I would have recommended them but now I won't. There are better places to enjoy a good meal.
Those who give it 5 stars have never been to a nice italian place, apparently. LaPalina is dull. Food is ok; service is most disappointing. At least it's inexpensive!
